Make a version subcommand to print the version

Add a `"version"` arm to the `match subcommand.as_str()` block:

```rust
        "version" => {
            println!("{}", env!("CARGO_PKG_VERSION"));
            Ok(())
        }
```

`env!("CARGO_PKG_VERSION")` is a built-in Rust macro that reads the `version` field from `Cargo.toml` at **compile time**, so it always stays in sync with the package version without any extra dependency or code.

Place it alongside the other arms, e.g. right after `"status"`:

```rust
        "status" => { ... }

        "version" => {
            println!("{}", env!("CARGO_PKG_VERSION"));
            Ok(())
        }

        "ssh" => { ... }
```

Also update the `other =>` error message so users know the subcommand exists:

```rust
        other => {
            eprintln!(
                "Unknown subcommand `{other}`. \
                 Usage: {program} <start|status|version|ssh|tmux> [args...]"
            );
            Err(format!("unknown subcommand: {other}").into())
        }
```

Now `gvm version` prints `1.0.6` (or whatever is currently in `Cargo.toml`).
